import os
import json

import pandas as pd

# Set the path to the directory containing the JSON files
json_dir = '~/Desktop/2023-04-14-job-search/2023-04-14-job-search-location-DC'

# Expand the tilde character to the full path
json_dir = os.path.expanduser(json_dir)

# Get a list of all the JSON files in the directory
json_files = [pos_json for pos_json in os.listdir(json_dir) if pos_json.endswith('.json')]

# Initialize an empty list to store the data
json_data_DC = []

# Loop over each JSON file and load it into a Python object
for file in json_files:
    with open(os.path.join(json_dir, file)) as json_file:
        data = json.load(json_file)
        json_data_DC.append(data)
In [81]:
df_dc = pd.DataFrame(json_data_DC)

titles = []
company_names = []
locations = []
vias = []
descriptions = []
job_highlights = []
related_links = []
extensions = []
detected_extensions = []
job_ids = []

# dict_keys(['title', 'company_name', 'location', 'via', 'description', 'job_highlights', 'related_links', 'extensions', 'detected_extensions', 'job_id'])
for document in df_dc.jobs_results:
    if type(document) == float:
        continue
    else:
        for item in document:
            titles.append(item['title'])
            company_names.append(item['company_name'])
            locations.append(item['location'])
            vias.append(item['via'])
            descriptions.append(item['description'])
            job_highlights.append(item['job_highlights'])
            related_links.append(item['related_links'])
            extensions.append(item['extensions'][0])
            detected_extensions.append(item['detected_extensions'])
            job_ids.append(item['job_id'])

# Set the path to the directory containing the JSON files for the nationwide job search results
json_dir_2 = '~/Desktop/2023-04-14-job-search/2023-04-14-job-search-location-DC'

# Expand the tilde character to the full path
json_dir_2 = os.path.expanduser(json_dir_2)

# Get a list of all the JSON files in the directory
json_files_2 = [pos_json for pos_json in os.listdir(json_dir_2) if pos_json.endswith('.json')]

# Initialize an empty list to store the data
json_data_USA = []

# Loop over each JSON file and load it into a Python object
for file in json_files_2:
    with open(os.path.join(json_dir_2, file)) as json_file:
        data = json.load(json_file)
        json_data_USA.append(data)

# dict_keys(['title', 'company_name', 'location', 'via', 'description', 'job_highlights', 'related_links', 'extensions', 'detected_extensions', 'job_id'])

for document in df_usa.jobs_results:
    if type(document) == float:
        continue
    else:
        for item in document:
            titles.append(item['title'])
            company_names.append(item['company_name'])
            locations.append(item['location'])
            vias.append(item['via'])
            descriptions.append(item['description'])
            job_highlights.append(item['job_highlights'])
            related_links.append(item['related_links'])
            extensions.append(item['extensions'][0])
            detected_extensions.append(item['detected_extensions'])
            job_ids.append(item['job_id'])

import re
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

keywords = ["data scientist","data analyst","neural networks","big data and cloud computing","machine learning","reinforcement learning","deep learning","time series","blockchain","natural language processing"]

counts = {}

for title in df_all['title']:
    title_lower = title.lower()
    matches = re.findall("|".join(keywords), title_lower)
    for match in matches:
        if match not in counts:
            counts[match] = 1
        else:
            counts[match] += 1

# make the dict in descending order
counts = dict(sorted(counts.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))

counts

# Function to clean the text data
def clean_text(text):
    # Tokenize the text
    words = word_tokenize(text)

    # Convert to lowercase and remove punctuation
    words = [''.join(c for c in w if c not in string.punctuation) for w in words]
    words = [w.lower() for w in words if w]

    # Remove stopwords
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    words = [w for w in words if w not in stop_words]

    return ' '.join(words)

import nltk
import string
import collections
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from wordcloud import WordCloud
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
from nltk.tokenize import word_tokenize

# Load your text data (replace with your own text data)
text = descriptions

# Function to clean the text data
def clean_text(text):
    # Tokenize the text
    words = word_tokenize(text)

    # Convert to lowercase and remove punctuation
    words = [''.join(c for c in w if c not in string.punctuation) for w in words]
    words = [w.lower() for w in words if w]

    # Remove stopwords
    stop_words = set(stopwords.words('english'))
    words = [w for w in words if w not in stop_words and len(w) >= 2]

    return words

# Clean the text data
cleaned_words = clean_text(text)

# Word count plot
word_count = collections.Counter(cleaned_words)
most_common_words = word_count.most_common(30)

labels, values = zip(*most_common_words)
indexes = range(len(labels))

# Define a list of colors for the bars
colors = ['orange', 'blue', 'green', 'red', 'purple', 'pink', 'brown', 'gray', 'teal', 'black'] * 3  # Repeat the colors to have enough colors for 30 bars

plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))
plt.bar(indexes, values, color=colors[:len(indexes)])
plt.xticks(indexes, labels, rotation='vertical')
plt.xlabel('Words')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.title('Top 30 Words')
plt.show()

df_all_job_highlights = pd.DataFrame()

qualifications = []
responsibilities = []

for i in df_all.job_highlights.values:
    if type(i) == float:
        continue
    else:
        for item in i:
            if 'title' in item.keys():
                if item['title'] == 'Qualifications':
                    qualifications.append(item['items'])
                elif item['title'] == 'Responsibilities':
                    responsibilities.append(item['items'])
                else:
                    continue
